BA Playoffs|2016]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n| 14 || '''14''' || '''33.7''' || .442 || .348 || '''.767''' || '''4.9''' || 3.9 || .4 || '''.2''' || 16.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018 NBA Playoffs|2018]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n| 5 || 5 || 31.2 || '''.467''' || '''.381''' || .682 || 2.6 || '''4.6''' || '''1.0''' || .0 || '''18.6'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 35 || 19 || 24.7 || .444 || .346 || .740 || 3.2 || 3.2 || .4 || .1 || 12.7\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Awards and accomplishments==\n*Won the gold medal at the [[2004 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship|FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (2004)\n*[[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian League]] Rookie of the Year (2005)\n*[[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian League]] All-Star (2005, 2006)\n*Winner of the [[FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Cup|FIBA Borislav Stankovi\u0107 Tournament]] (2007, 2010)\n*Won the Slovenian League national championship (2008)\n*Won the MVP award for the [[FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Cup|FIBA Borislav Stankovi\u0107 Tournament]] (2010)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bscup.tom.com/2010-08-02/0PRO/57714990.html?source=POST_GZW |title=Dragic Honored with MVP, Yi Entered Best Team_2010 DONGFENG YUEDA KIA STANKOVIC CONTINENTAL CUP |publisher=Bscup.tom.com |date=1 August 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406040906/http://bscup.tom.com/2010-08-02/0PRO/57714990.html?source=POST_GZW |archive-date=6 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Named Western Conference Player of the Week, 4/2-4/8 (Houston, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Rockets' Dragi\u0107, Heat's James named Players of the Week|url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/index.html?ls=iref:nbahpt2|accessdate=10 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411152554/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/index.html?ls=iref:nbahpt2|archive-date=11 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Member of the [[EuroBasket All-Tournament Team]] ([[2013 Eurobasket|2013]])\n*Named Western Conference Player of the Week, 1/27-2/2 (Phoenix, 2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragi\u0107 Named Western Conference Player of Week|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/dragic-named-western-conference-player-week}}</ref>\n*Contestant for the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge|Taco Bell Skills Challenge]] (2014)\n*Member of the 20-50-40 Club (2014)\n*Won the [[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player of the Year Award]] (2014)\n*Jabolko Navdiha ''(Apple of Inspiration)'' by President of the Republic of Slovenia (2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragic presented with 'Apple of Inspiration' from Slovenian president|url=https://www.thescore.com/news/507207|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n*Member of the [[All-NBA team|All-NBA Third Team]] (2014)\n*[[FIBA EuroBasket MVP]] (2017)\n*Member of the [[EuroBasket All-Tournament Team]] ([[2017 Eurobasket|2017]])\n*[[NBA All-Star]] (2018)\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Sports}}\n* [[List of European basketball players in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{basketballstats|nba=goran_dragic|bbr=d/dragigo01}}\n*[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/Goran%20DRAGIC/pid/46941/_//players.html Goran Dragi\u0107] at fiba.archive.net\n*[https://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=THB#!careerstats Goran Dragi\u0107] at euroleague.net\n\n{{Miami Heat current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{2008 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA Most Improved Players}}\n{{EuroBasket MVP Award}}\n{{Slovenia Squad EuroBasket 2017}}\n{{Slovenian Sportsman of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dragic, Goran}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2006 FIBA World Championship players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIBA World Championship players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup players]]\n[[Category:ABA League players]]\n[[Category:CB Murcia players]]\n[[Category:FIBA EuroBasket-winning players]]\n[[Category:Houston Rockets players]]\n[[Category:KD Ilirija players]]\n[[Category:KK Olimpija players]]\n[[Category:Liga ACB players]]\n[[Category:Miami Heat players]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association players from Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Suns players]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Spurs draft picks]]\n[[Category:Saski Baskonia players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in Spain]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Slovenian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Slovenian people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ljubljana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Goran Dragi\u0107\n| image = EuroBasket 2017 Finland vs Slovenia 37 (Goran Dragi\u0107 cropped 2).jpg\n| caption = Dragi\u0107 with Slovenia in 2017\n| alt = \n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 190\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Miami Heat\n| number = 7\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1986|5|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Ljubljana]], [[SR Slovenia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality = Slovenian\n| draft_year = 2008\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 45\n| draft_team = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| career_start = 2003\n| career_end =\n| years1 = 2003\u20132004\n| team1 = [[KD Ilirija|Ilirija]]\n| years2 = 2004\u20132006\n| team2 = [[KD Slovan|Geoplin Slovan]]\n| years3 = 2006\u20132007\n| team3 = [[CB Murcia|Murcia]]\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008\n| team4 = [[KK Olimpija|Union Olimpija]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2008|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2010|end}}\n| team5 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years6 = {{nbay|2010|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}\n| team6 = [[Houston Rockets]]\n| years7 = 2011\n| team7 = [[Saski Baskonia]]\n| years8 = {{nbay|2012|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2014|end}}\n| team8 = Phoenix Suns\n| years9 = {{nbay|2014|end}}\u2013present\n| team9 = [[Miami Heat]]\n| highlights =\n*[[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2018}})\n*[[All-NBA Team|All-NBA Third Team]] ({{nbay|2013|end}})\n*[[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player]] ({{nbay|2013|end}})\n*[[FIBA EuroBasket MVP]] ([[EuroBasket 2017|2017]])\n*[[FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Cup]] MVP ([[2010 FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Continental Champions' Cup|2010]])\n*[[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian League]] champion (2008)\n*Slovenian League All-Star (2006)\n*Slovenian League Rookie of the Year (2005)\n*[[Slovenian Sportsman of the year]] (2017)\n| profile = goran_dragic\n| bbr = dragigo01\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|SLO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 2017|2017 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2004 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship|2004 Brno]]|[[Slovenia men's national under-20 basketball team|Under-20 Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Goran Dragi\u0107''' (born 6 May 1986) is a Slovenian professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Miami Heat]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He plays at both the [[point guard]] and [[shooting guard]] positions. He played professional basketball in Slovenia and Spain before entering the NBA in 2008.<ref name=SeptemberSign>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/news/sign_dragic_080825.html |title=Suns Sign Goran Dragic &#124; The Official Site Of The Phoenix Suns |publisher=Nba.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 has played for the [[Phoenix Suns]] twice, the [[Houston Rockets]], and the Heat. He was an [[All-NBA Third Team]] selection and the [[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player]] with the Suns in 2014. He was named an [[NBA All-Star]] for the first time in 2018 with Miami. He led the senior [[Slovenian national basketball team|Slovenian national team]] to its first [[FIBA EuroBasket]] title in [[EuroBasket 2017|2017]], while being named the [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP|Most Valuable Player of the tournament]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Europe===\nDragi\u0107 began his professional career in 2003, at the age of 17, in the [[Slovenian Second Basketball League]] with [[KD Ilirija]]. He played there for one year, before transferring to the top level [[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian Basketball League]] and [[NLB League|Adriatic League]] club [[KD Slovan|Slovan]], in 2004. After spending two years with Slovan, he transferred to the [[Liga ACB|Spanish ACB League]] club [[Saski Baskonia]], who [[loan (sports)|loaned]] him to the Spanish club club [[CB Murcia|Murcia]], in 2006.\n\nDragi\u0107 joined the Slovenian club [[KK Union Olimpija|Union Olimpija]] in 2007, and he played there during the 2007\u201308 season, winning the Slovenian League championship with the team.\n\n===NBA===\n====Phoenix Suns (2008\u20132011)====\nDragi\u0107 entered the [[2008 NBA draft]], where he was selected in the second round, 45th overall, by the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. His draft rights were then traded to the [[Phoenix Suns]] in exchange for the draft rights to [[Malik Hairston]], the 48th pick.  After the Suns finished a deal with [[Saski Baskonia|TAU Ceramica]] (now known as Caja Laboral), with whom he was under contract, they officially signed him on 22 September 2008.<ref name=SeptemberSign/> The Suns hoped that he would take over the starting point guard position after [[Steve Nash]] relinquished it.<ref name=SeptemberSign/><ref name=DecemberArticle12>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2008/12/11/20081211sunsdebut1212.html |title=New suns may play tonight |publisher=Azcentral.com |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> On 25 January 2010, Dragi\u0107 scored a then career high 32 points, hitting 6 of 7 three-pointers in a losing effort against the Utah Jazz.<ref>{{cite web|author=Loren Jorgensen |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705361116/Utah-Jazz-Little-known-Dragic-enjoys-career-night-for-Suns.html |title=Utah Jazz: Little-known Dragic enjoys career night for Suns |publisher=Deseret News |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2010, during [[2010 NBA Playoffs#(3) Phoenix Suns vs. (7) San Antonio Spurs|game 3 of the Western Conference Semifinals]], he led a Phoenix Suns comeback against the team that originally drafted him, the San Antonio Spurs, scoring 23 of his total 26 points in the fourth quarter. Dragi\u0107 scored his points on 10/13 FG attempts including 5/5 three-pointers and a 4-point play, as the Suns overcame an early 18-point deficit to defeat the Spurs 110\u201396 and take a 3\u20130 lead in their best of seven series in the Western Conference Semifinals. \"I think it's safe to say that may have been the best fourth-quarter performance I have ever seen in a playoff game\", Suns forward [[Grant Hill]] said.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=300507024 |title=Phoenix Suns vs. San Antonio Spurs - Recap - May 07, 2010 - ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Houston Rockets (2011\u20132012)====\nOn 24 February 2011, Dragi\u0107 was traded to the [[Houston Rockets]] along with a protected first-round pick in exchange for [[Aaron Brooks (basketball)|Aaron Brooks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2011/02/24/20110224phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-aaron-brooks-houston-rockets-nba-trade.html |title=Phoenix Suns trade Goran Dragic for Aaron Brooks from Houston Rockets |publisher=azcentral.com |date= |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/sports/rockets/article/Rockets-trade-Battier-Brooks-in-separate-deals-1549128.php |title=Rockets trade Battier, Brooks in separate deals |work=Houston Chronicle |date= |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref> On 13 April 2011, in the Rockets' season finale, Dragi\u0107 recorded his first career triple-double with 11 points, 11 assists and 11 rebounds in a 121\u2013102 win over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=310413016|title=Rockets send Timberwolves to 15th straight loss|work=ESPN.com|date=13 April 2011|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2011 NBA lockout]], he played for [[Saski Baskonia]] of Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/euroleaguenews/transactions/2011-12-signings/i/89886/5611/caja-laboral-tabs-guard-dragic |title=CAJA LABORAL tabs guard Dragic - 2011-12 SIGNINGS - Welcome to EUROLEAGUE BASKETBALL |publisher=Euroleague.net |date=20 November 2011 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> He played for a brief period of time there until the lockout ended. He returned to the Rockets for the 2011\u201312 season. Throughout most of the season, Dragi\u0107 continued to be used as a bench player as a means to help the Rockets out during the lockout shortened season. In March 2012, he filled in for [[Kyle Lowry]], who was out with a bacterial infection. On 9 April 2012, Dragi\u0107 won the Western Conference Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/ |title=Rockets' Dragic, Heat's James named Players of the Week |publisher=NBA.com |date=9 April 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309150917/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/ |archivedate=9 March 2014  }}</ref>\n\n====Second stint with the Suns (2012\u20132015)====\nIn 2012, Dragi\u0107 became an unrestricted free agent. He agreed to sign a 4-year, $30 million deal with a player option on the final year with the [[Phoenix Suns]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spotrac.com/nba/phoenix-suns/goran-dragic/ |title=Goran Dragic Salary Cap, Contracts, Salaries, Cap Hits, & News Profile |publisher=Spotrac.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> and officially became a member of the team again on 19 July 2012. He was brought in to replace [[Steve Nash]], whom he played behind during his first stint with the Suns, as starting point guard. On 19 February 2013, Dragi\u0107 recorded a career-high 18 assists to go with 14 points as the Suns defeated the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] 102\u201398. Dragi\u0107 nearly recorded a [[triple-double]] against the [[Brooklyn Nets]] with 31 points, 12 assists, and 9 rebounds on 24 March 2013. Despite suffering through a 25\u201357 season, Dragi\u0107 ended up gaining some career high moments in the process.\n\nAfter getting [[Eric Bledsoe]] from a trade with the [[Los Angeles Clippers]], the Suns ultimately decided to move Dragi\u0107 to the shooting guard position as a means of putting less pressure on Dragi\u0107 to distribute the ball to his teammates. In his first game playing with Bledsoe as a teammate, Dragi\u0107 led the team with 26 points and 9 assists in a 104\u201391 season opening victory over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]]. Dragi\u0107 had over 8 games with 30 points or more, including a double-double of 31 points and 10 assists in a victory against the Portland Trail Blazers on 27 November 2013. He also had what was, at the time, a career-high 33 points in a loss to the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] on 2 January 2014. On 3 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 won his second career Western Conference Player of the Week award and his first with the Suns for games played between 27 January \u2013 2 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/02/03/lowry-dragic-named-players-of-week/index.html |title=Lowry, Dragic named Players of the Week |publisher=NBA.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204162228/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/02/03/lowry-dragic-named-players-of-week/index.html |archive-date=4 February 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Three days later, he was paired with [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] guard [[Reggie Jackson (basketball, born 1990)|Reggie Jackson]] in the revamped, team-based Skills Challenge at the All-Star weekend\n\nOn 8 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 scored a career-high 34 points\u2014 while attempting only 13 field-goals\u2014 to go along with 10 assists in a 122\u2013109 home victory over the [[Golden State Warriors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140208/GSWPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Suns 122, Warriors 109 |work=NBA.com |date=8 February 2014 |accessdate=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518132219/http://www.nba.com/games/20140208/GSWPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=18 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 23 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 scored a new career-high 35 points, along with 3 assists and 3 steals, in a 112\u2013115 loss to the Houston Rockets.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140223/HOUPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Rockets 115, Suns 112 |access-date=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526135405/https://www.nba.com/games/20140223/HOUPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|7jVMxL7-YPk|Goran Dragic Scores a Career-High 35 Points}}</ref> On 28 February 2014, he recorded a new career-high 40 points, along with 3 rebounds and 5 assists, in a 116\u2013104 win over the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140228/NOPPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Suns 116, Pelicans 104 |access-date=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526140935/https://www.nba.com/games/20140228/NOPPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Kp7ZqDY6vPg|Goran Dragic Scores a Career High... for the Second Time This Week!}}</ref> He became the first player, since [[Rod Strickland]] in 1985\u201386, to set career highs in points three times in a single month. Dragi\u0107 also became the sixth player, after his head coach [[Jeff Hornacek]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dirk Nowitzki]], [[LeBron James]], and [[Kevin Durant]], to join the 20-50-40 Club \u2014 averaging 20 or more points per game while shooting 50%+ from the field and 40%+ on three-pointers.<ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/4/7/5588628/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-about-to-join-exclusive-20-50-40-club</ref><ref>http://valleyofthesuns.com/2014/04/16/goran-dragic-joins-hornacek-petrovic-on-exclusive-list/</ref> He also averaged over 5 assists per game throughout the season as well, leaving him joining the likes of [[Larry Bird]], [[Jeff Hornacek]] and [[LeBron James]].<ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/4/23/5643752/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-named-nbas-most-improved-player-for-2013-14</ref><ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/6/4/5779748/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-named-to-2013-14-all-nba-third-team</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2014, Dragi\u0107 won the 2014 [[NBA Most Improved Player Award]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/04/23/goran-dragic-wins-kia-most-improved-player-award/ |title=Suns' Dragic wins Kia Most Improved Player award |access-date=23 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128094023/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/04/23/goran-dragic-wins-kia-most-improved-player-award/ |archive-date=28 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> One month later, he would end up being honored by his home nation with their national \"Apple of Inspiration\" award for being a role model and inspiring hope in Slovenia, as well as helping out the nation's community with humanitarian activities.<ref>[http://www.sta.si/en/vest.php?s=a&id=2012201 Basketball Player Dragi\u0107 Honoured by President Pahor]</ref> Finally, on 4 June 2014, Dragi\u0107 was named to the 2014 [[All-NBA team|All-NBA third team]] alongside [[Damian Lillard]], [[LaMarcus Aldridge]], [[Al Jefferson]] and [[Paul George]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/06/04/2013-14-all-nba-teams/ |title=Durant, LeBron headline 2013-14 All-NBA First Team |access-date=4 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604220936/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/06/04/2013-14-all-nba-teams/ |archive-date=4 June 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Miami Heat (2015\u2013present)====\n[[File:Goran Dragic (30303474504).jpg|thumb|Dragi\u0107 with the Heat in 2016.]]\nOn 19 February 2015, Dragi\u0107 and his brother, Zoran, were traded to the [[Miami Heat]] in a three-team deal also involving the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-acquire-goran-dragic-and-zoran-dragic|title=HEAT Acquire Goran Dragic and Zoran Dragic|date=19 February 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> Two days later, he made his debut for the Heat, recording 12 points and 3 rebounds in a 105\u201391 loss to the New Orleans Pelicans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150221/NOPMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223235430/http://www.nba.com/games/20150221/NOPMIA/gameinfo.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 February 2015|title=Pelicans lose Davis and Anderson, roll past Heat 105-91|date=21 February 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 finished the season averaging 16.6 points and 5.3 assists per game in 26 starts for Miami, as the Heat missed the playoffs.\n\nOn 9 July 2015, Dragi\u0107 re-signed with the Heat to a five-year, $90 million contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=HEAT Re-Signs Goran Dragic|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-re-signs-goran-dragic|accessdate=13 July 2015|work=NBA.com|date=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Stein | first = Marc | title = Goran Dragic, Miami Heat agree to five-year, $90 million deal | url = http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/13179887/goran-dragic-miami-heat-reach-agreement-five-year-90-million-deal | work = ESPN.com | date = 1 July 2015 | accessdate = 1 July 2015}}</ref> In January 2016, he missed eight straight games because of a left calf injury.<ref>{{cite web | last = Braun | first = Rick | title = Miami Heat guard Goran Dragic likely to return Friday night vs. Bucks | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/nba/miami-heat/article57195813.html | work = MiamiHerald.com | date = 28 January 2016 | accessdate = 30 January 2016}}</ref> On 20 February 2016, he recorded a season-high 24 points, eight assists and seven rebounds in a 114\u201384 win over the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Whiteside has 25 points, 23 rebounds; Heat beat Wizards|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160220/WASMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=21 February 2016|work=NBA.com|date=20 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209230443/http://www.nba.com/games/20160220/WASMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He bested that season high on 11 March, recording 26 points and nine assists in a 118\u201396 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic scores 26 as Heat beat Bulls 118-96|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160311/MIACHI/gameinfo.html|accessdate=11 March 2016|work=NBA.com|date=11 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108011007/http://www.nba.com/games/20160311/MIACHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 April, he recorded 16 points and a career-high 12 rebounds in a 106\u201398 win over the Chicago Bulls, helping the Heat sweep the season series with the Bulls for the first time since the 2003\u201304 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heat rally past Bulls, 106-98 for 46th win of the season|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160407/CHIMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=NBA.com|date=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124735/http://www.nba.com/games/20160407/CHIMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the Heat's second-round playoff match-up with the Toronto Raptors, Dragi\u0107 scored a postseason career-high 30 points to help the Heat to a 103\u201391 victory in Game 6, tying the series at 3\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic, Wade lead Heat past Raptors 103-91 _ and into Game 7|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160513/TORMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=14 May 2016|work=NBA.com|date=13 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124900/http://www.nba.com/games/20160513/TORMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Heat went on to lose Game 7, bowing out of the playoffs with a 4\u20133 defeat.\n\nOn 28 November 2016, Dragi\u0107 recorded season highs of 27 points and 17 assists in a 112\u2013104 loss to the Boston Celtics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899706|title=Thomas scores 25, Celtics get past Heat 112-104|work=ESPN.com|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> He topped that mark on 6 December 2016, scoring 29 points (his highest-scoring total as a member of the Heat at the time) in a 114\u2013103 loss to the [[New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899758|title=Anthony scores 35, Knicks beat depleted Heat 114-103|work=ESPN.com|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 set a new season high six days later, scoring 34 points in a 112\u2013101 win over the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899805|title=Dragic scores 34, Heat beat Wizards 112-101 to snap slide|work=ESPN.com|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> On 6 February 2017, he scored 33 points and hit a career-high seven three-pointers to lead the Heat to their 11th straight victory with a 115\u2013113 win over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900180|title=Dragic leads Heat to 11th straight win, 115-113 over Wolves|work=ESPN.com|date=6 February 2017|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 November 2017, Dragi\u0107 scored a season-high 29 points in a 126\u2013115 win over the Phoenix Suns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974913|title=Goran Dragic scores season-high 29, Heat beat Suns 126-115|work=ESPN.com|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref> On 27 November 2017, he was named the Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played Monday, 20 November through Sunday, 26 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-named-eastern-conference-player-week|title=Goran Dragic Named Eastern Conference Player of the Week|work=NBA.com|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> On 15 January 2018, he was named the Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played Monday, 8 January through Sunday, 14 January. It was his fourth career Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-named-eastern-conference-player-week-0|title=Goran Dragi\u0107 Named Eastern Conference Player Of The Week|work=NBA.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref> On 1 February, Dragi\u0107 was named the replacement for [[Kevin Love]] on Team [[LeBron James|LeBron]] for the [[2018 NBA All-Star Game]], thus making him an All-Star for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic Selected to 2018 NBA All-Star Team|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/dragic-selected-to-2018-nba-all-star-team|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=NBA.com|date=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2018, Dragi\u0107 scored 28 points in a 120\u2013111 win over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]], becoming the first [[Slovenia]]n player to reach the 10,000-point mark in the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070760|title=Dragic scores 28, Heat outlast Trail Blazers 120-111|work=ESPN.com|date=27 October 2018|accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref> In late November and early December, he missed eight games with a sore right knee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071057|title=Adebayo's career-high 22 points helps Heat beat Suns 115-98|work=ESPN.com|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref> On 19 December, he underwent successful surgery to clean up his right knee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-undergoes-surgery-181219|title=Goran Dragi\u0107 Undergoes Surgery|work=NBA.com|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> He returned to action on 23 February 2019 against the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071561|title=Pistons reach 7th in East, top reeling Heat 119-96|work=ESPN.com|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=24 February 2018|quote=Miami got point guard Goran Dragic on the floor for the first time since Dec. 10, after a two-month rehab to recover from right knee surgery.}}</ref> On 28 March, he recorded his second career triple-double with 23 points, 12 rebounds and 11 assists in a 105\u201399 win over the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071797|title=Dragic's triple-double lifts Heat past Mavs, 105-99|work=ESPN.com|date=28 March 2019|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\n===Slovenian junior national team===\nDragi\u0107 won the gold medal at the [[2004 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] with the [[Slovenia men's national under-20 basketball team|Slovenian under-20 junior national team]]. He also played at the [[2005 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]].\n\n===Slovenian senior national team===\n[[File:Slovenia vs. Serbia at EuroBasket 2009 (36).jpg|thumb|Dragi\u0107 playing with [[Slovenian national basketball team|Slovenia]] at the [[2009 EuroBasket]]]]\nDragi\u0107 competed with the senior men's [[Slovenia national basketball team|Slovenian national basketball team]] at the [[2006 FIBA World Championship]] and the [[2007 EuroBasket]], in limited roles. Dragi\u0107's role with the Slovenian national basketball team began to increase in the [[2009 EuroBasket]] and the [[2010 FIBA World Championship]]. He then played with his brother [[Zoran Dragi\u0107|Zoran]] in the [[2011 EuroBasket]] and the [[2013 EuroBasket]], the latter which was held in [[Slovenia]]. During the 2013 tournament, Goran and his brother helped lead Slovenia to a 5th-place finish and a spot in the [[2014 FIBA World Cup]]. Dragi\u0107 finished in the 2013 EuroBasket's top five in points and assists, which earned him a spot on the [[EuroBasket All-Tournament Team|All-Tournament Team]]. In 2014, Dragi\u0107 was named Slovenia's [[captain (sports)|team captain]] after [[Jaka Lakovi\u010d]] retired from [[national sports team|national team]] play. In the [[friendly game]]s before the [[2014 FIBA World Cup]], Dragi\u0107 was rested in 9 of their 14 games, before actually playing in the official tournament's matches. After finishing up their friendly games, Dragi\u0107 played with no restrictions beyond the rest of the competition; he was the only [[All-NBA Team]] member to play in the 2014 FIBA World Cup, aside from the [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|Team USA]] members.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nPrior to the [[2017 EuroBasket]], Dragi\u0107 announced that he would retire from playing with the Slovenian national team after the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-heat/fl-sp-miami-heat-goran-dragic-s20170829-story.html |title=Miami Heat guard Goran Dragic to retire from international play after EuroBasket |first=Ira |last=Winderman |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |location=[[Deerfield Beach, Florida]] |date=29 August 2017 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> At the tournament, he helped Slovenia to win its first ever FIBA European championship. He scored 35 points, on 12-22 shooting in the [[EuroBasket 2017 Final|final]], which was the most points scored in a final, since [[Pau Gasol]] scored 36 points in the [[EuroBasket 2003|2003]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heatzone.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2017/09/17/goran-dragic-leads-slovenia-to-eurobasket-gold-with-35-points-named-mvp-of-tournament/|title=Goran Dragic leads Slovenia to EuroBasket gold with 35 points - Heat Zone|publisher=|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Following his performance, Dragi\u0107 was given the [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP|Most Valuable Player award of the tournament]], after averaging 22.6 points per game, in 9 games played.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/title-hero-dragic-caps-off-fairy-tale-finish-with-mvp-honors|title=Title hero Dragic caps off fairy tale finish with MVP honors|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=MVP>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/title-hero-dragic-caps-off-fairy-tale-finish-with-mvp-honors|title=Title hero Dragic caps off fairy tale finish with MVP honors|publisher=fiba.basketball|date=17 September 2017}}</ref> Following that performance, he was named the 2017 [[Slovenian Sportsman of the year]].\n\n==Personal life==\nDragi\u0107 was born to a Slovenian mother and a Serbian father.<ref>[http://www.downtownphoenixjournal.com/2010/02/04/suns-spot-el-dragon/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302192458/http://www.downtownphoenixjournal.com/2010/02/04/suns-spot-el-dragon/|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> He grew up in Slovenia playing [[Association football|football]]. However, an injury forced him to switch sports. As a child, he admired NBA players [[Michael Jordan]], [[Allen Iverson]] and former teammate [[Steve Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html|title=Goran Dragic Stats, Video, Bio, Profile|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=1 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025071832/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html|archivedate=25 October 2013}}</ref> He is fluent in [[Slovene language|Slovenian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]], Spanish, and English.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://nba.us/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html |title=Goran Dragic Stats, Video, Bio, Profile &#124; NBA.com |publisher=Nba.us |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Dragi\u0107's younger brother, [[Zoran Dragi\u0107|Zoran]], was formerly his teammate on the Phoenix Suns and Miami Heat,<ref>{{cite news|title=Suns Sign Zoran Dragi\u0107|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/press-release/suns-sign-zoran-dragic|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=30 September 2014|work=NBA.com}}</ref> and currently plays in Germany for [[ratiopharm Ulm]].<ref>{{cite news|title=EA7 Milan inks Dragic at guard|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/746egud9j589imq6/ea7-milan-inks-dragic-at-guard|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=Euroleague.net|date=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Dragi\u0107 married his long-time girlfriend, Maja.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delo.si/sport/eurobasket/dragic-vzel-le-en-prost-dan-da-se-je-ozenil.html |title=Dragi\u0107 vzel le en prost dan, da se je o\u017eenil |publisher=Delo.si |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siol.net/sportal/kosarka/ep2013/novice/2013/08/sloveniji_bo_zdaj_poveljeval_poroceni_dragic.aspx |title=Sloveniji bo zdaj poveljeval poro\u010deni Dragi\u0107 &#124; EP 2013 - Planet |publisher=Siol.net |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> In November 2013, Dragi\u0107's first son, Mateo, was born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valleyofthesuns.com/2013/11/11/defense-has-helped-the-suns-become-the-nbas-surprise-team/ |title=Defense has helped the Suns become the NBA's surprise team |publisher=Valleyofthesuns.com |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe and Zoran, alongside teammates [[Markieff Morris|Markieff]] and [[Marcus Morris (basketball)|Marcus Morris]], all briefly played together for the Suns during the fourth quarter of their 112\u201396 victory over the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] on 2 January 2015. It marked the first time in the NBA's history that two different pairs of brothers played together for the same team at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150102/PHIPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Green helps Suns pull away from 76ers, 112-96 |access-date=9 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901084149/http://www.nba.com/games/20150102/PHIPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=1 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[President of Republika Srpska]] [[Milorad Dodik]] honored Dragi\u0107 with an Order of Njego\u0161 and a Medal of Merit for the People, in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goran Dragi\u0107 posetio Igokeu, Dodik ga odlikovao Njego\u0161evim ordenom |url=https://www.b92.net/sport/kosarka/vesti.php?yyyy=2018&mm=08&dd=15&nav_id=1431133 |website=b92.net |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nDragi\u0107 is an [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox Christian]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sem Slovenec , pravoslavne vere. Na dana\u0161nji praznik ti \u017eelim, mir v du\u0161i in radost v srcu. |url=https://twitter.com/Goran_Dragic/status/1082307839467708416 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041c\u0418\u0420 \u0411\u041e\u0416\u0418\u0408\u0418, \u0425\u0420\u0418\u0421\u0422\u041e\u0421 \u0421\u0415 \u0420\u041e\u0414\u0418! |url=https://twitter.com/reno_968/status/1082306420123545600 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2008\u201309 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 55 || 1 || 13.2 || .393 || .370 || .769 || 1.9 || 2.0 || .5 || .1 || 4.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2009\u201310 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| '''80''' || 2 || 18.0 || .452 || .394 || .736 || 2.1 || 3.0 || .6 ||