{"title_page": "List of massacres in Canada", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}} \n{{more citations needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nThis is a list of events in [[Canada]] for which one of the commonly accepted names includes the word '''''[[massacres]]'''''. ''Massacre'' is defined in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'' as \"the indiscriminate and brutal slaughter of people or (less commonly) animals; carnage, butchery, slaughter in numbers\". It also states that the term is used \"in the names of certain massacres of history\". Thomas W. Gallant definition of ''Massacres''; deliberate slaughter of a large number of people in a violent way, especially when they cannot defend themselves.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gallant|first1=Thomas W.|authorlink=Thomas Gallant (historian)|title=review of Levene, Roberts The Massacre in History|journal=Crime, History & Societies|date=2001|volume= 5|issue= 1}}</ref><ref Name=DictionaryDefinition>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mastsacre?s=t \"massacre.\" Dictionary.com Unabridged. Random House, Inc. December 23, 2014.]</ref>  The following is a list of [[massacre]]s that have occurred in [[Canada]] and its predecessors. Some events in which numerous individuals were [[wound]]ed are also included.\n\n:*For '''single perpetrator events and shooting sprees''', see [[List of rampage killers|Lists of rampage killers]] and [[:Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n:*For '''school shootings''', see [[:Category:School shootings in Canada]]/[[:Category:School killings in Canada]]\n:*For '''North American First Nations massacres''', see [[List of Indian massacres|List of American First Nations massacres]].\n:*For '''terrorism''', see [[Terrorism in Canada]].\n:*For '''serial killers''', see [[List of serial killers by country#Canada|List of serial killers in Canada]].\n==List==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"\"width:120px;\"\"|Name\n! style=\"\"width:65px;\"\" data-sort-type=\"\"date\"\" |Date\n! style=\"\"width:120px;\"\"|Location\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Dead / Injured / Captives\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Mechanism of injury\n! style=\"\"width:25px;\"\"|Perpetrator suicide\n!class=\"\"unsortable\"\"|Notes\n|-\n|[[Lachine massacre]]\n|August 5, 1689\n|[[Lachine, Quebec]]\n| est. 24 to 250\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| Total population of Lachine estimated at 375.  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Battle at Port-la-Joye|Port-la-Joye Massacre]]\n|July 11, 1746\n|Port-la-Joye, \u00cele Saint-Jean.  The location now known as [[Hillsborough River (Prince Edward Island)]].\n|34 / 0\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| Acadian and Mi'kmaqs killed 34 unarmed British (27 soldiers and 7 sailors).  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Battle of Grand Pr\u00e9|Grand-Pr\u00e9 Massacre]]\n|February 10, 1747\n|[[Grand-Pr\u00e9, Nova Scotia]]\n|67 / 0 / 40\n|Military and allies\n|na\n| Acadian and Mi'kmaqs took est. 40 prisoners after attack.  Part of [[King George's War]]\n|-\n|[[Raid on Dartmouth|Dartmouth Massacre]]\n|May 13, 1751\n|[[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]]\n|bet. 7 and 20 / 0 / bet. 6 and 14 \n|First Nations violence\n|na\n| One of seven raids by Mi'kmaqs on British and New England forces, usually very violence with deaths and scalpings.  Part of [[Father Le Loutre's War]]\n|-\n|[[St. Francis Raid|St. Francis Massacre]]\n|October 4, 1759\n|[[Odanak]], [[Quebec]]\n|30\u2013200 / unk / bet. 7 and 20\n|Military and allies\n|na\n| Raid by [[Robert Rogers (British Army officer)|Robert Rogers]]' Rangers, which was pursued and depleted before crossing back into New England.  Part of [[French and Indian War]]\n|-\n|[[Bruce Blackman murders]]\n|January 18, 1983\n|[[Coquitlam]], [[British Columbia]]\n|6\n|Long gun, blunt instrument\n|No\n|Bruce Alfred Blackman murdered 6 members of his family and was found not guilty by reason of insanity.<ref>https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/01/18/Police-layed-six-charges-of-first-degree-murder-Tuesday-against/8504411714000/</ref> He was remanded in custody indefinitely at the Forensic Psychiatric Center in Coquitlam.<ref>http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/oic/arc_oic/1122_1991</ref><ref>https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/02/09/Bruce-Blackman-was-found-unfit-to-stand-trial-Wednesday/3337413614800/</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bloody Falls Massacre]]\n|July 17, 1771\n|The location now known as [[Kugluk/Bloody Falls Territorial Park]] near [[Kugluktuk, Nunavut]]\n|20\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n|Alleged massacre between indigenous peoples\n|-\n|[[Chilcotin War]]\n|April 30, 1864\n|[[Bute Inlet]], [[British Columbia]]\n|19\n|First Nations violence\n|na\n|Massacre of road workers in a series of attacks by indigenous peoples\n|-\n|[[Cypress Hills massacre]]\n|June 1, 1873\n|[[Cypress Hills (Canada)|Cypress Hills]], [[Saskatchewan]]\n|23\n|Civilian violence\n|na\n| Mass murder perpetrated by American bison and wolf hunters, and American and Canadian whisky traders and cargo haulers, against a camp of Assiniboine people. One of the main contributing reasons for the formation of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]].\n|-\n|[[Black Donnellys]] massacre\n|February 4, 1880\n|[[Lucan Biddulph]], [[Ontario]]\n|5\n|Civilian violence\n|na\n| Murder of five members of the Donnelly family by an armed mob, after which their farm was burned down. The event was the culmination of long-standing conflict between the family and other residents, none of the mob were ever convicted.\n|-\n|[[Frog Lake Massacre]]\n|April 2, 1885\n|[[Frog Lake, Alberta]]\n|9\n|Military\n|na\n|part of the [[North-West Rebellion]]\n|-\n|[[Canadian Pacific Air Lines Flight 108]]\n|September 9, 1949\n|[[Sault-au-Cochon, Quebec]]\n|23\n|Explosives\n| No\n|Time bomb onboard [[DC-3]] airliner plotted by [[Albert Guay]] to murder his spouse for the insurance payout.\n|-\n|[[Shell Lake murders]]\n|August 15, 1967\n|[[Shell Lake, Saskatchewan]]\n|9\n|\n| \n| Mass murder of nine members of the Peterson family on their farm, targeted randomly by [[Victor Ernest Hoffman]].\n|-\n|[[Buffalo Narrows axe slayings]]\n|January 30, 1969<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_zVgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zm8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=6853,4087414&dq=la+loche&hl=en | title=Seven murder counts laid in northern axe deaths | publisher=The Phoenix | date=January 31, 1968 | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n|[[Buffalo Narrows, Saskatchewan]]\n|7\n|Axe\n| \n|Seven members of the Pederson family were murdered with an axe in their beds by Frederick Moses McCallum.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/buffalo-narrows-50-years-pederson-1.4997319 | title=Generations of grief: Family still reeling 50 years after little-known mass axe murder| publisher= Bridget Yard \u00b7 CBC News | date=February 2, 2019 | accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dale Nelson]] murders\n|September 4, 1970\n|[[Creston, British Columbia]]\n|8\n|\n| \n|Perpetrator engaged in [[cannibalism]], [[necrophilia]], and [[pedophilia]]\n|-\n|[[Kettle Valley#1972 shooting|Kettle Valley shooting]]\n|August 28, 1972\n|[[Kettle Valley|Kettle Valley, British Columbia]]\n| 6\n| Long gun\n| No\n|After absconding from a secure psychiatric hospital, 27-year-old William Bernard Lepine (also called William McConnell) killed 6 people and injured 3 others using a .22-calibre rifle and a .30-calibre rifle. Attacks occurred at four different locations in the Kettle Valley on a single day. Located and apprehended by police the next day. At trial, was found Not Guilty by Reason of Insanity on six counts of murder. Psychiatric evidence indicated that he suffered from schizophrenia with nihilistic delusions and believed he was chosen to save the world from a [[nuclear holocaust]] by killing the victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/blackpress/docs/i20120905104109575|title=Arrow Lakes News, September 05, 2012|work=Issuu|access-date=March 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2agSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=g_cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3519,4203016&dq=&hl=en|title=The Bulletin - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ML0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=He0FAAAAIBAJ&hl=de&pg=1214,5708172|title=Ottawa Citizen - Google News Archivsuche|website=news.google.com|access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OHBkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mH0NAAAAIBAJ&hl=de&pg=1076,3787333|title=The Calgary Herald - Google News Archivsuche|website=news.google.com|access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\"\n|-\n|[[Blue Bird Caf\u00e9 fire|Blue Bird Caf\u00e9 Fire]]\n|September 1, 1972\n|[[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n|37\n| Arson\n| \n| A fire was started in a stairwell of the building by 3 men.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/281340/40-years-later-montreal-commemorates-victims-of-the-blue-bird-fire/|title=40 years later \u2013 Montreal commemorates victims of the Blue Bird fire|work=Global News|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.ca/ontv/titledetails.aspx?titleid=86157|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719195514/http://www.history.ca/ontv/titledetails.aspx?titleid=86157|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-19|title=Out of the Blue - Disasters of the Century - History Television|date=2011-07-19|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Pius X High School shooting]]\n|October 27, 1975\n|[[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n| 2\n| Long gun\n| \n|Five injured, 1 killed prior to school incident\n|-\n|[[Wells Gray Provincial Park Family Murders]]\n|August 2, 1982\n|[[Wells Gray Provincial Park]], [[British Columbia]]\n|6\n|\n| \n|Three generations of a family were murdered by David Shearing 18&nbsp;km (11.2&nbsp;mi) North of [[Clearwater, British Columbia|Clearwater]], [[British Columbia]]\n|-\n|[[Denis Lortie|National Assembly shootings]]\n|May 8, 1984\n|[[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n|3\n| Stolen military\n| No\n|3 killed and 13 wo